data.sampled: A Dowker-Thistlethwaite code is a 4-tuple representing a knot in 3-dimensional space. The first, third and fourth element in the 4-tuple determine the crossing number of the knot, while the second element determines the orientation of the knot. The unknotting number can be determined by summing the absolute value of the crossing number and the absolute value of the second element of the 4-tuple. The absolute value of the sum is the unknotting number. It tells how many times the knot can be untied - loosely speaking. In a knot theory problem this is an important property. If you have a knot and you twist it a number of times equal to its unknotting number it will come undone. If you twist it less, it will have more or less complicated forms depending on the knot (some knots will indeed come apart with just a few twists), if you twist it more it will become more complicated and have some knot inside the other one.
